# Accessibility â€” WCAG 2.1 Level AA

Apply these rules when writing or modifying any HTML in this project.

## Document-level

- Always set `lang` attribute on `<html>` (e.g. `lang="en"`).
- Include a skip navigation link as the first focusable element in `<body>`:
  `<a href="#main" class="skip-link">Skip to main content</a>`

## Landmarks

- Use semantic landmark elements: `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<footer>`, `<aside>`, `<section>`.
- Do NOT add redundant ARIA roles to native landmarks (e.g. no `role="navigation"` on `<nav>`).
- If multiple `<nav>` or `<section>` elements exist, give each a unique `aria-label`.

## Headings

- Exactly one `<h1>` per page.
- Never skip heading levels (e.g. `<h2>` followed by `<h4>`).
- Every `<section>` should begin with a heading.

## Images

- All `<img>` elements must have an `alt` attribute.
- Decorative images use `alt=""`.
- Informative images have concise, descriptive alt text (no "image of" or "picture of" prefixes).

## Links and buttons

- Use `<a>` for navigation, `<button>` for actions. Never use `<div>` or `<span>` as interactive elements.
- Link and button text must be descriptive. Avoid "click here", "read more", "learn more" without context.
- If the visible text is insufficient, use `aria-label` or `aria-labelledby`.
- Links opening in a new window should indicate this (e.g. via visually hidden text or `aria-label`).

## Forms

- Every form input must have an associated `<label>` element (via `for`/`id` pairing or wrapping).
- Use `<fieldset>` and `<legend>` for groups of related inputs.
- Provide visible error messages associated with inputs via `aria-describedby`.

## Color and contrast

- Text contrast ratio: at least 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text (18px+ bold or 24px+).
- Never convey information through color alone.

## Keyboard

- All interactive elements must be keyboard-accessible.
- Never use `tabindex` values greater than 0.
- Ensure a logical focus order that matches the visual layout.

## Media

- Provide text alternatives for non-text content.
- Video/audio must have captions or transcripts.
